# Types

## Flash Converter
![[Pasted image 20250925163252.png]]
- Apply input voltage across a reference voltage and a voltage divider
- Comparators connected to each level
- Can only tell which two reference voltage levels the input voltage lies between
### Characteristics
- Very fast
- Inaccurate/low resolution
## Successive Approximator
![](data:image/png;base64,)
- Successively approximate input voltage using a binary search and a DAC
- Bit by bit, set the DAC output voltage. Repeat the following
	- Set next bit input for DAC to 1
	- Wait for DAC and comparator to stabilize
	- If the DAC output (test voltage) is higher than the input, set the current bit to 1, else clear current bit to 0
### Characteristics
- Slower than flash converter but more accurate
## Dual Slope Integrator
![](data:image/png;base64,)
- Input signal $V_{a}$ is generated for a fixed time
- Input is switched to the negative reference and the negative reference is then integrated until the integrator output is zero
- The time required to integrate the signal back to zero is used to compute the value of the signal
- Accuracy dependent of $V_{ref}$ and timing
### Characteristics
- Noise tolerant and very accurate
- Typically slow conversion rates (Hz to a few kHz)
# How to Use
## Configure
- Turn on ADC Clock
- Set GPIO port to analog mode
- Enable ADC
- Wait until ADC ready
- Choose input channel
- Set sample time
## Usage
- Start conversion by writing to start conversion register
- Either poll until complete or use interrupt
## Conversion Formulas
$$D=\lfloor\left( \frac{V_{in}-V_{ref-}}{V_{ref+}-V_{ref-}} (2^{n}-1)\right)\rfloor$$
$V_{in} \approx \left( D \times \frac{V_{ref+}-V_{ref-}}{2^{n}-1} \right)+V_{ref-}$
